Introduction

This document analyzes the relationship between the percentage of the population using the internet and the female labor force participation rate across different countries for the year 2022. The data is sourced from the World Bank.

Research Question and Hypothesis

Research Question: Is there a relationship between internet usage and female labor force participation rates across countries?

Hypothesis: We expect to find a positive relationship between internet usage and female labor force participation. Our reasoning:

  1. Access to opportunities: Internet access provides women with better access to job opportunities, including remote work positions that may not be available locally.

  2. Flexibility: Online platforms and digital tools enable flexible work arrangements that can help women balance work and family responsibilities more effectively.

  3. Economic development: Higher internet usage is typically associated with more developed economies, which tend to have more gender-equal labor markets and better infrastructure supporting womens workforce participation.

  4. Education and skills: Internet access facilitates online education and skill development, potentially increasing womens employability.

However, we acknowledge that this relationship may be complex and influenced by many cultural, economic, and social factors that vary across countries.

1. Data Preparation

First, we load the necessary libraries. We will be using the tidyverse package for data manipulation and visualization, and the WDI package to download data directly from the World Bank.

# install.packages("tidyverse") # Run this line if you don't have tidyverse installed
# install.packages("WDI") # Run this line if you don't have WDI installed
library(tidyverse)
library(WDI)

Now, we download the data directly from the World Bank using the WDI package. We need two indicators: - IT.NET.USER.ZS: Internet usage (% of population) - SL.TLF.CACT.FE.ZS: Female labor force participation rate (%)

# Define the indicators we want to download
indicators <- c("IT.NET.USER.ZS", "SL.TLF.CACT.FE.ZS")

# Download the data from the World Bank for the year 2022
wb_data <- WDI(country = "all",
               indicator = indicators,
               start = 2022,
               end = 2022,
               extra = TRUE)

# Prepare the data
final_data <- wb_data %>%
  select(country, IT.NET.USER.ZS, SL.TLF.CACT.FE.ZS) %>%
  rename(Country.Name = country,
         internet_usage = IT.NET.USER.ZS,
         female_labor_force = SL.TLF.CACT.FE.ZS) %>%
  na.omit()

# Display the first few rows of the final dataset

4. Extreme Values Analysis

We identify and examine extreme values (outliers) in our dataset using the IQR method.

# Function to detect outliers using IQR method
detect_outliers <- function(x) {
  q1 <- quantile(x, 0.25)
  q3 <- quantile(x, 0.75)
  iqr <- q3 - q1
  lower_bound <- q1 - 1.5 * iqr
  upper_bound <- q3 + 1.5 * iqr
  return(x < lower_bound | x > upper_bound)
}

# Detect outliers for internet usage
internet_outliers <- final_data[detect_outliers(final_data$internet_usage), ]
if(nrow(internet_outliers) > 0) {
  internet_outliers_sorted <- internet_outliers[order(internet_outliers$internet_usage), 
                                                 c("Country.Name", "internet_usage", "female_labor_force")]
  knitr::kable(internet_outliers_sorted, 
               col.names = c("Country", "Internet Usage (%)", "Female Labor Force (%)"),
               caption = "Countries with Extreme Internet Usage Values",
               row.names = FALSE,
               align = c('l', 'r', 'r'))
}

# Detect outliers for female labor force
labor_outliers <- final_data[detect_outliers(final_data$female_labor_force), ]
if(nrow(labor_outliers) > 0) {
  labor_outliers_sorted <- labor_outliers[order(labor_outliers$female_labor_force), 
                                          c("Country.Name", "internet_usage", "female_labor_force")]

5. Correlation Analysis

Now, well quantify the linear relationship between our two variables by calculating the Pearson correlation coefficient. The coefficient ranges from -1 (perfect negative correlation) to +1 (perfect positive correlation). A value near 0 suggests no linear correlation.

# Perform correlation test
cor_test <- cor.test(final_data$internet_usage, final_data$female_labor_force)

# Create a nice table for correlation results
cor_results <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("Correlation Coefficient", "t-statistic", "p-value", "95% CI Lower", "95% CI Upper"),
  Value = c(
    round(cor_test$estimate, 4),
    round(cor_test$statistic, 4),
    round(cor_test$p.value, 4),
    round(cor_test$conf.int[1], 4),
    round(cor_test$conf.int[2], 4)
  )
)

knitr::kable(cor_results, 
             col.names = c("Metric", "Value"),
             caption = "Pearson Correlation Test Results",
             align = c('l', 'r'))
Pearson Correlation Test Results
Metric Value
Correlation Coefficient -0.0597
t-statistic -0.8483
p-value 0.3973
95% CI Lower -0.1958
95% CI Upper 0.0786

Interpretation: The correlation coefficient of -0.06 indicates a very weak negative relationship between internet usage and female labor force participation. This result is contrary to our initial hypothesis that predicted a positive relationship. The correlation is not statistically significant (p-value > 0.05), suggesting that at the country level, internet usage alone does not predict female labor force participation. This finding highlights that cultural, economic, and policy factors may play more important roles than technology access.

6. Scatter Plot and Visual Analysis

A scatter plot is the best way to visualize the relationship between two continuous variables. We will also add a regression line to see the trend more clearly.

ggplot(final_data, aes(x = internet_usage, y = female_labor_force)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, color = "steelblue", size = 2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "red", se = TRUE) + # "lm" stands for linear model
  labs(
    title = "Internet Usage vs. Female Labor Force Participation (2022)",
    x = "Internet Usage (% of population)",
    y = "Female Labor Force Participation (%)",
    caption = "Source: World Bank World Development Indicators"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Interpretation: The scatter plot reveals a nearly flat relationship between the two variables, consistent with the weak correlation coefficient. The red regression line has a slight negative slope, but the wide confidence interval (gray band) indicates high uncertainty. The plot shows substantial variation in female labor force participation even among countries with similar internet usage levels, suggesting that other factors beyond internet access are more important determinants of womens workforce participation. We can see clusters of countries with high internet usage but varying levels of female participation (40-80%), which further supports that the relationship is not straightforward.

Conclusion

This analysis examined the relationship between internet usage and female labor force participation across 203 countries in 2022. The data revealed several key findings:

Key Findings:

  1. Weak Negative Correlation: The correlation coefficient of -0.06 indicates a very weak negative relationship between internet usage and female labor force participation. This suggests that, contrary to what might be expected, higher internet usage is not associated with increased female labor force participation at the country level.

  2. Internet Usage: The average internet usage across countries was 67.7%, with a wide range from 11% to 100%. The median of 76.5% suggests that most countries have relatively high internet penetration.

  3. Female Labor Force Participation: The average female labor force participation rate was 50.6%, ranging from 5.2% to 82.6%. This wide variation highlights significant global disparities in womens workforce participation.

Limitations and Future Research:

  • This analysis only captures a snapshot from 2022 and does not account for temporal trends or causality.
  • Country-level aggregation may mask important within-country variations and regional differences.
  • Other confounding factors such as cultural norms, economic development, education levels, and childcare availability were not considered.
  • Future research could explore longitudinal data to understand how changes in internet access over time relate to changes in female labor force participation, and could include additional socioeconomic variables for a more comprehensive analysis.
